nter" data-align="center">20.9%</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Ideal Body Fat By Age</figcaption></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Why Our Body Fat Calculator Is Reliable</strong></h2>



<p>Body fat calculators need to be built on foundational scientific methods that have been well-researched. This ensures an accurate estimation that’s been created from informed information. That’s exactly what you get with our body fat calculator.</p>



<p>The <a href="https://academic.oup.com/milmed/article/180/1/91/4159972" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">U.S. Navy’s</a> body fat formula is used to inform the main calculations. It&#8217;s something that’s been used throughout research for decades due to its excellent reliability.</p>



<p>What makes it great is the fact that you can estimate body fat using simple body measurements. Alongside this, it takes factors such as gender differences and age into account. These are things that may influence the overall results.</p>



<p>With this, differences in fat distribution can be analyzed to give a much more accurate output.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Our body fat calculator stands out from the rest because it’s built on a foundation of well-researched and widely accepted scientific methods. Alongside this, it cross-references the results with the BMI method of measuring health status. Doing this ensures the output results are consistent with health standards&nbsp;</p>



<p>The tables above provide some useful comparisons that allow you to better manage your health status. Using these can help to inform motivations to find your ideal body fat percentage.</p>



<p>When we put these things together, we have a handy estimation tool that’s easy to use for all ability levels. The simplified process means that all you need is a tape measure and yourself.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Risks Of Overweight And Obesity</strong></h2>



<p>When comparing your body fat results to the reference ranges, there are certain <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6088226/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">risks to bear in mind</a>. These are some of the main ones to consider:&nbsp;</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>Type 2 Diabetes — </strong>This occurs when your body is unable to properly regulate and use sugar as fuel. Being overweight or obese may cause your body to become resistant to the hormone insulin or not produce enough. <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7903505/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">Type 2 diabetes</a> can cause chronic blood sugar imbalance, requiring medical intervention.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Cardiovascular Disease — </strong>This relates to <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7123129/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">chronic cardiovascular conditions</a> such as heart disease and stroke. Being overweight or obese can lead to high blood pressure and cholesterol, both of which are big risk factors. In 2021, cardiovascular disease accounted for <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10809869/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">20.5 million deaths</a>, which is almost one-third of total deaths globally.</li>



<li><strong>Fatty Liver Disease — </strong>Caused by a build-up of excess fat in the liver. The <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/1422-0067/23/24/16226" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">two main types</a> are non-alcoholic fatty liver disease and alcoholic fatty liver disease. If left to progress, this can cause chronic inflammation and cirrhosis, or permanent scarring.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Metabolic Syndrome — </strong>This refers to a cluster of <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5933580/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">different medical conditions</a>. Examples include high blood pressure, high blood sugar, excess cholesterol, and excess abdominal fat. Put together, these increase the risk of chronic conditions such as diabetes, stroke, and heart disease.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Gut Imbalance — </strong>The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4566439/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">gut microbiome</a> refers to a collection of microbes in our gut that support energy production, immune function, and digestion. If this becomes disrupted, it may lead to gut issues that require medical intervention. This can cause several health issues including <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6039952/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">irritable bowel syndrome</a>, metabolic disease, and <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/15/14/3258" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">mental health issues</a>.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Reproductive Health Conditions — </strong>Reproductive system issues can affect both men and <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10803652/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">women</a>. These include infertility, pregnancy, and childbirth complications, and irregular menstrual cycles.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Mental Health Conditions — </strong>Several mental health issues can be linked to the physical problems of being overweight or obese. Managing stress caused due to discrimination and stigma can have wide-ranging effects. These include <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9460559/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">anxiety</a>, depression, low self-esteem, and body dissatisfaction.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Sleep Apnea And Respiratory Problems — </strong>Being overweight or obese can lead to respiratory issues or make existing ones worse. Examples include <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5836788/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">breathing difficulties</a> or periods where breathing stops when sleeping. Over time, this can lead to chronic daytime fatigue and an increased risk of heart disease.&nbsp;</li>



<li><strong>Joint Pain — </strong>As we move around and exercise, our joints need to support our body structure. Excess body weight can cause increased joint pressure, especially in the lower back, hips, and knees. This can lead to joint pain, soreness, and chronic degenerative conditions such as <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9289681/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">osteoarthritis</a>.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">How To Reduce Body Fat</h2>



<p>Reducing body fat requires a structured, long-term approach. Following the tips below can help you to adopt a holistic approach to long-term weight management.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Go Slow</h3>



<p>When losing weight, most people tend to think that a faster approach will lead to quicker weight loss. While this may be the case initially, this doesn’t tend to be the case long-term.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Losing weight requires gradual, systematic changes. Phrases like “Tomorrow, I’ll eat well, work out, and go to bed early” fail to address the long-term mindset needed. These kinds of habits require many steps and should slowly be built over time.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Juggling our social lifestyles and professional responsibilities requires a structured approach. Adding healthier habits to this means we need to adapt each lifestyle component to suit one another.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Rather than trying to reinvent the wheel straight away, start with small changes that can gradually be built in. Set small, manageable goals that can be built on before progressing to the bigger ones. Focusing on one manageable healthy habit at a time has been shown to lead to <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7135855/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">better long-term success</a>.&nbsp;</p>



<p>For example, adding more fruits and vegetables is an easy, achievable goal that can be built on when accomplished. It&#8217;s specific, measurable, achievable, realistic, and time-bound. This aligns with the smart goal-setting principle.&nbsp;</p>



<p>When you have this, think about what it will achieve to accomplish the goal. Could this be planning a weekly shopping trip so that there is always fruit in the house? Could this also mean ensuring the freezer is always well stocked on frozen vegetables so you have stocks in reserve?</p>



<p>Working on these manageable, realistic habit changes helps to build a solid foundation to build on. Setting unrealistic goals and forcing yourself to adopt habits that you don’t enjoy is unsustainable.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Prioritize Whole Foods</strong></h3>



<p>Whole foods are minimally processed which means they maintain their natural state. Because of this, they’re full of <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/15/13/2888" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">vitamins</a>, minerals, and fiber. These perform several vital functions in the body including energy production, immune function, and hormone regulation.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Good examples of whole foods include fruits, vegetables, legumes, nuts, and seeds. Eating more whole foods rich in fiber and <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7539343/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">protein</a> helps improve satiety, which refers to the state of feeling full.&nbsp;</p>



<p>When consumed in the right amounts, this can prevent snacking and overeating. Over a longer-term period, this can help maintain a calorie deficit which is a key factor for weight loss.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Alongside this, whole foods tend to be lower in sugar and unhealthy fats. These can help to <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyt.2018.00545/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">decrease sugar cravings</a> and balance blood sugar levels. To prioritize whole foods, a practical tip is to eat the rainbow. This means adding a colored whole food to a meal or snack.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Manage Stress</h3>



<p>When thinking about health, physical health is often seen as the most vital component. However, when we view health holistically, we start to see the links between our mental health and physical aspects. Managing this effectively can improve aspects of our physical health which includes our body composition.</p>



<p>Chronic stress elevates the level of <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27345309/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">cortisol</a>, a stress regulation hormone that constantly fluctuates in our body. While a normal level of cortisol is needed, chronically elevated levels can negatively affect metabolism and lead to weight gain.</p>



<p>Therefore, practicing self-care routines and stress-relieving activities should form a vital part of a weight maintenance routine. For example, a lack of sleep can disturb hormonal balance which can decrease metabolic rate. This is associated with <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9031614/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">weight gain</a> and possible <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9031614/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">mental health issues</a> over a longer period.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Increase Cardio</h3>



<p>When performing cardio exercise, the body <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7898283/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">requires more energy</a> to sustain the correct movement patterns. In the immediate period following, it needs more energy to perform recovery processes such as tissue repair and energy production.&nbsp;</p>



<p>This increase in energy expenditure can help to maintain energy balance. As a key contributor to weight gain, this can help to reduce body fat when done using enough volume.</p>



<p>Cardio exercise doesn’t have to mean using the treadmill or elliptical for hours on end. You can also use inventive and fun ways to get your heart rate up and burn more energy. This could include taking a walk in the park or signing up for a fun dance class with your friends.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Try Strength Training</h3>



<p>Alongside cardio training, strength training can form part of a well-organized exercise routine. When done correctly, <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/354108151_The_Mechanisms_of_Muscle_Mass_and_Strength_Increase_during_Strength_Training" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">strength training</a> helps to build muscle mass. Muscle uses more energy than fat, meaning that a higher muscle mass increases your metabolic rate.</p>



<p>When looking to reduce body fat, strength training can form a vital part of your training routine. While a fancy gym is great, you can also use a mat and a suitable floor space at home. The main point is to be consistent with your strength training and find something that you enjoy doing.</p>



<p>When building muscle mass, ensure you follow the basic principles of resistance training. Volume is a key determinant, which refers to the amount of work performed. If in doubt, enlist the help of a qualified health professional such as a personal trainer.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Create A Caloric Deficit</h3>



<p>When it comes to fat loss, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8120623/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">energy balance</a> is a key factor. This refers to the balance between the energy you take in and the energy you use or burn.</p>



<p>A calorie deficit is needed for successful fat loss. This means that you burn more calories or energy than you consume. This can be accomplished through exercise, diet, or a combination of both.</p>



<p>Generally speaking, a calorie deficit of approximately <a href="https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/educational/lose_wt/recommen.htm" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">500–1000 calories per day</a> is recommended. This should be done for 8–12 weeks, allowing a break before starting again. This helps to provide long-term, sustainable weight loss of around 1–2 pounds per week.&nbsp;</p>



<p>When creating a calorie deficit, it&#8217;s important not to overly restrict yourself. We need a certain amount of calories and essential body fat to survive. Too much restriction can lead to malnutrition and possible health issues that negatively contribute to overall health status.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Use your <a href="https://bfpt.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s43161-023-00139-6" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">basal metabolic rate</a> or BMR to estimate the amount of calories your body needs at rest. Adding a physical activity level gives you your baseline maintenance calorie intake which you can base your deficit on.</p>



<p>Remember that overly restrictive diets increase the chances of disordered eating habits and reduce the possibility of long-term success. When creating a calorie deficit, it&#8217;s important to use a gradual approach that suits your circumstances. This allows healthy weight loss and avoids the possibility of crash dieting or unhealthy rebounds.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Bottom Line</h2>



<p>Making positive health changes by reducing body fat and changing lifestyle habits doesn’t happen overnight. It takes time and patience to use a structured approach built on solid scientific principles.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The body fat calculator provides a handy estimation of your current body fat levels using basic physiological characteristics. It uses foundational scientific principles to give you a trustworthy estimate that can be used to improve health. Use it alongside the tips above to improve your body fat levels and promote long-term, sustainable lifestyle changes.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1725875669020"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Is fat so bad?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Having a certain amount of body fat isn’t bad at all. It&#8217;s essential for survival and needed for insulation, energy, and organ protection. Excess body fat, however, can lead to negative health issues such as diabetes and cardiovascular disease.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1725875680610"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Is BMI the same as percent body fat?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Body mass index, or BMI, is different from percent body fat. BMI uses your height and weight to categorize your health status according to certain ranges. Body fat percentage can more accurately estimate your actual body fat composition.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1725875695711"><strong class="schema-faq-question">How long does it take to lose 10% body fat?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">The process of losing weight is highly variable between individuals. Factors such as your starting weight, gender, age, activity level, and health status all contribute. Therefore, a specific timeframe cannot be given.</p> </div> </div>
